===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|boy|boy|lang=enm}}, {{term|boye||servant, commoner, knave, boy|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{recons|boia|bōia|boy|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|bōjô||younger brother, young male relation|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|bō-||brother, close male relation|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bʰā-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|bʰāt-||father, elder brother, brother|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|boy||boy|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frs|-}} {{term|boi||boy, young gentleman|lang=frs}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|boai||boy|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|boi||boy|lang=dum}}, and probably to the {{etyl|ang|-}} proper name ''Bōia''. Also related to {{etyl|vls|-}} {{term|boe||brother|lang=vls}}, Norwegian dialectal {{term|boa||brother|lang=no}}, Dutch {{term|boef||rogue, knave|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} dialectal {{term|Bube||boy, lad, knave|lang=de}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|bófi||rogue, crook, bandit, knave|lang=is}}. See also {{l|en|bully}}.

